WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:10.000
From the Library of Congress and the Smithsonian National Museum of African American History and Culture.

00:00:10.000 --> 00:00:16.000
We're on the road again. There we go.

00:00:16.000 --> 00:00:26.000
This is David Klein for the Smithsonian and the National Museum of African American History and Culture and the Library of Congress.

00:00:26.000 --> 00:00:31.000
Today is Friday March the 1st and I'm in Berlin, Gain, California.

00:00:31.000 --> 00:00:33.000
And Mr. Steve McNichols, good morning.

00:00:33.000 --> 00:00:34.000
Good morning.

00:00:34.000 --> 00:00:36.000
Thank you very much for talking with us today.

00:00:36.000 --> 00:00:38.000
The pleasure is mom.

00:00:38.000 --> 00:00:48.000
Okay. What I'd like to do, Steve, is first just ask you to tell us a little bit about where you were raised and the family that you were raised in.

00:00:48.000 --> 00:00:54.000
Yeah, I'd like to dwell for just a moment on my origins if I may because it's important.

00:00:54.000 --> 00:01:09.000
My maternal grandparents, yet so I can own a Frank, emigrated from Eastern Europe, Riga (Latvia) and Marijampolė to Palestine in 1890.

00:01:10.000 --> 00:01:15.000
And we're part of an emigration movement sponsored by the Rothschild.

00:01:15.000 --> 00:01:18.000
In fact, I'm thinking it works for the Rothschild.

00:01:18.000 --> 00:01:29.000
And they moved to Palestine where they found in, or one of 11 families who founded the city of Tel Aviv,

00:01:30.000 --> 00:01:40.000
which instantaneously gives me more status in Israel than I ever have anywhere else, you know.

00:01:40.000 --> 00:01:44.000
And their names are engraved on Founders Monument.

00:01:44.000 --> 00:01:48.000
I have a picture of my uncle standing in front of Founders Monument.

00:01:48.000 --> 00:01:57.000
And my grandfather built the first residential dwelling home in Tel Aviv.

00:01:58.000 --> 00:02:05.000
It's a part of me, which is on a tour, a lot of the tours that go through Tel Aviv.

00:02:05.000 --> 00:02:08.000
And my mother was born there.

00:02:08.000 --> 00:02:15.000
And then when my mother was five years old, my grandmother was having health problems.

00:02:15.000 --> 00:02:26.000
So they separated and she moved to Geneva with my grandparents and my mother relocated to Geneva.

00:02:26.000 --> 00:02:38.000
Where she became a classically trained violinist and was Joseph Szigeti's prodigy people and toured with them before coming to the United States.

00:02:38.000 --> 00:02:42.000
Which was probably a mistake. I think the whole family should have stayed in Geneva.

00:02:42.000 --> 00:02:45.000
That's where their hands were at.

00:02:45.000 --> 00:02:53.000
But they moved to what the United States, along with André Kostelanetz and some other people.

00:02:53.000 --> 00:03:01.000
And that background is very important to me, even though I'm not observant, not an observant too.

00:03:01.000 --> 00:03:08.000
But it's important to me as a person, you know, and something I feel strongly about.

00:03:08.000 --> 00:03:15.000
So I was born in New York in 1939.

00:03:15.000 --> 00:03:21.000
My mother was here at this classically trained violinist.

00:03:21.000 --> 00:03:28.000
Her violin was stolen as soon as she hooked up with my father, no connection.

00:03:28.000 --> 00:03:32.000
And she stopped playing violin for 14 years.

00:03:32.000 --> 00:03:38.000
My father was brought up in a very tough neighborhood in St. Louis.

00:03:38.000 --> 00:03:42.000
He was a thunk who was murdered when my father was three.

00:03:42.000 --> 00:03:48.000
And my father was a very tough guy.

00:03:48.000 --> 00:03:56.000
Very smart, actually. Intellectually curious, well-rained, read.

00:03:56.000 --> 00:03:59.000
But I think he got a GED.

00:03:59.000 --> 00:04:05.000
And I didn't appreciate him enough as a child.

00:04:05.000 --> 00:04:09.000
Because I was supposed to be a genius.

00:04:09.000 --> 00:04:13.000
And I discovered what the word percussius really means.

00:04:13.000 --> 00:04:18.000
It means that your way ahead of everybody else up to about age 13,

00:04:18.000 --> 00:04:23.000
and then your parents start passing you.

00:04:23.000 --> 00:04:28.000
And instead of being, you know, so much more brilliant than they are,

00:04:28.000 --> 00:04:32.000
you're lucky to stay in the top thurn.

00:04:32.000 --> 00:04:38.000
I mean, but we lived in a very tough neighborhood in New York.

00:04:38.000 --> 00:04:41.000
133rd Street, you know.

00:04:41.000 --> 00:04:44.000
I was the only white kid in my neighborhood.

00:04:44.000 --> 00:04:51.000
And but I went to Dalton School when in most prestigious private schools in the country

00:04:51.000 --> 00:04:54.000
on a full scholarship.

00:04:54.000 --> 00:05:01.000
So during the day I was going to school with children of some of the wealthiest people in the country.

00:05:01.000 --> 00:05:09.000
(W. Averell) Harriman, nephew, Marshall Field III's niece, and others, many others.

00:05:09.000 --> 00:05:12.000
And then I would return to the ghetto at night.

00:05:12.000 --> 00:05:16.000
And it was an economist who gets what it exists since for me.

00:05:16.000 --> 00:05:20.000
Because I was very sensitive and very impressionable,

00:05:20.000 --> 00:05:25.000
very conscious of the fact that I came from a very poor background

00:05:25.000 --> 00:05:29.000
and lived in a very poor neighborhood.

00:05:29.000 --> 00:05:33.000
What was the racial ethnic composition of that neighborhood?

00:05:33.000 --> 00:05:37.000
I was the only white kid in the neighborhood.

00:05:37.000 --> 00:05:40.000
Puerto Rican.

00:05:40.000 --> 00:05:47.000
And I was lucky because it still was not as bad as he's told me.

00:05:47.000 --> 00:05:49.000
It was bad.

00:05:49.000 --> 00:05:54.000
I finally went to work one day in small bodily line in the street.

00:05:54.000 --> 00:06:00.000
And because I lived there, I grew up there.

00:06:00.000 --> 00:06:04.000
I got along with the other kids pretty much.

00:06:04.000 --> 00:06:06.000
We had fights.

00:06:06.000 --> 00:06:09.000
When other than that I was accepted.

00:06:09.000 --> 00:06:14.000
I was Steve who was kind of the strange kid who lived in the neighborhood.

00:06:14.000 --> 00:06:18.000
So being that you had this, you know, we were like in this in the neighborhood.

00:06:18.000 --> 00:06:21.000
In the neighborhood and they're going to Dalton School,

00:06:21.000 --> 00:06:29.000
were you thinking about race and difference in class at all the young age you remember?

00:06:29.000 --> 00:06:31.000
It was in the air.

00:06:31.000 --> 00:06:36.000
I couldn't help but think about it because I was surrounded by it.

00:06:36.000 --> 00:06:40.000
But my goal was to get the hell out of them.

00:06:40.000 --> 00:06:44.000
And my mother was driving me to succeed.

00:06:44.000 --> 00:06:50.000
So I wouldn't have the same kind of life that she had.

00:06:50.000 --> 00:06:53.000
What did your father do for work?

00:06:53.000 --> 00:06:55.000
Whatever he could.

00:06:55.000 --> 00:07:00.000
I mean, he had very as sort of an uninteresting job.

00:07:00.000 --> 00:07:06.000
He worked in a lab, animal facility.

00:07:06.000 --> 00:07:12.000
But through his credit, just to show you what kind of a man he was,

00:07:12.000 --> 00:07:17.000
he started taking electronics courses.

00:07:17.000 --> 00:07:23.000
And taught himself radio and television electronics

00:07:23.000 --> 00:07:27.000
and then became a trainee for Picker X-Ray Corporation.

00:07:27.000 --> 00:07:32.000
And most of his peers had engineering degrees.

00:07:32.000 --> 00:07:39.000
And he was the top trainee in his training class when they were best repairmen.

00:07:39.000 --> 00:07:43.000
So he was remarkable really in his own way.

00:07:43.000 --> 00:07:47.000
I couldn't have done that.

00:07:47.000 --> 00:07:50.000
So my phone separated.

00:07:50.000 --> 00:07:57.000
My mother was very anxious to leave my father, which was really a mistake.

00:07:57.000 --> 00:08:01.000
And we separated.

00:08:01.000 --> 00:08:08.000
And remarkably, she supported herself by teaching French to employees of time life

00:08:08.000 --> 00:08:11.000
and started making a very good living.

00:08:11.000 --> 00:08:15.000
The first time we had money in my life.

00:08:15.000 --> 00:08:22.000
And then, unfortunately, she developed psychiatric symptoms

00:08:22.000 --> 00:08:29.000
and had a big breakdown in the middle of the time life lobby

00:08:29.000 --> 00:08:32.000
at noon one day.

00:08:32.000 --> 00:08:34.000
And she was institutionalized.

00:08:34.000 --> 00:08:36.000
The whole thing fell apart.

00:08:36.000 --> 00:08:39.000
And I went back to living with my father.

00:08:39.000 --> 00:08:43.000
I was 16.

00:08:43.000 --> 00:08:48.000
And my father really stepped into the bridge,

00:08:48.000 --> 00:08:51.000
because I'm not sure it was necessary that he'd do.

00:08:51.000 --> 00:08:55.000
But he really came through like Gamebusters,

00:08:55.000 --> 00:08:59.000
even though we never really got along.

00:09:03.000 --> 00:09:06.000
But he really saved my neck,

00:09:06.000 --> 00:09:09.000
psychiatric, like speaking.

00:09:09.000 --> 00:09:13.000
And I went into a permanent depression.

00:09:13.000 --> 00:09:18.000
Every day of my life since about age 15,

00:09:18.000 --> 00:09:25.000
I suffered from suicidal ideation for 15 years.

00:09:25.000 --> 00:09:28.000
Until we discovered when I was 65 years old,

00:09:28.000 --> 00:09:32.000
that I actually have a bipolar condition.

00:09:32.000 --> 00:09:37.000
Once we started training that, the depression lifted.

00:09:37.000 --> 00:09:41.000
And I started, I became much more fortunate, as a person.

00:09:41.000 --> 00:09:42.000
What did you do?

00:09:42.000 --> 00:09:45.000
What was the treatment for bipolar?

00:09:45.000 --> 00:09:48.000
What was the treatment for bipolar?

00:09:48.000 --> 00:09:50.000
Lithium.

00:09:50.000 --> 00:09:52.000
But I didn't get any treatment,

00:09:52.000 --> 00:09:54.000
because I wasn't diagnosed as bipolar.

00:09:54.000 --> 00:09:58.000
So my whole life was spent seeing chiroats

00:09:58.000 --> 00:10:01.000
who were treating me for depression,

00:10:01.000 --> 00:10:06.000
when they should have been treating me for bipolar condition.

00:10:06.000 --> 00:10:11.000
Not one of them guessed there was a bipolar condition.

00:10:11.000 --> 00:10:15.000
It was only by accident when this came in age 65.

00:10:15.000 --> 00:10:18.000
When my cardiologist, I returned from accident,

00:10:18.000 --> 00:10:21.000
where I've been living.

00:10:21.000 --> 00:10:24.000
And sent me for a panel of tests.

00:10:24.000 --> 00:10:26.000
One of the tests, you know,

00:10:26.000 --> 00:10:30.000
the lab technician wrote down that my lithium serum level

00:10:30.000 --> 00:10:33.000
was virtually non-existent.

00:10:33.000 --> 00:10:37.000
When it turns out, which is not really in thinking of a beam

00:10:37.000 --> 00:10:44.000
by a Portland, but triggered an investigation, you know, a review.

00:10:44.000 --> 00:10:50.000
But so starting in your teens, you're...

00:10:50.000 --> 00:10:56.000
Well, the whole episode with my mother being in situation,

00:10:56.000 --> 00:11:01.000
was very living with my mother for two years watching.

00:11:01.000 --> 00:11:04.000
The tearing of it, it's like the accurately,

00:11:04.000 --> 00:11:06.000
was extremely depressing.

00:11:06.000 --> 00:11:07.000
You know?

00:11:07.000 --> 00:11:10.000
I was extremely isolated.

00:11:10.000 --> 00:11:12.000
I mean, I had friends,

00:11:12.000 --> 00:11:15.000
but I was in a world by myself.

00:11:15.000 --> 00:11:20.000
My mother and I were both seen as psychiatrist,

00:11:20.000 --> 00:11:25.000
who was, in my opinion, totally irresponsible and unprofessional.

00:11:25.000 --> 00:11:32.000
And when he concluded that we both had psychiatric problems,

00:11:32.000 --> 00:11:35.000
he just ran in the opposite direction,

00:11:35.000 --> 00:11:38.000
instead of helping us deal with it.

00:11:38.000 --> 00:11:41.000
I'll never forget them.

00:11:41.000 --> 00:11:43.000
You know?

00:11:43.000 --> 00:11:48.000
I'd like to run into them now, if I had any strength.

00:11:48.000 --> 00:11:51.000
It was very sad.

00:11:51.000 --> 00:11:54.000
On the other hand,

00:11:54.000 --> 00:11:58.000
to musical ashamed, it was a tremendous learning experience.

00:11:58.000 --> 00:12:06.000
So, that was around age 16,

00:12:06.000 --> 00:12:07.000
so you're the next couple of years?

00:12:07.000 --> 00:12:11.000
It was when I turned my 16th part to...

00:12:11.000 --> 00:12:16.000
March of 15th.

00:12:16.000 --> 00:12:19.000
I was going to fly, I think.

00:12:19.000 --> 00:12:22.000
So, take me for the next couple of years?

00:12:22.000 --> 00:12:26.000
Well, I was going to start this in high school.

00:12:26.000 --> 00:12:30.000
And my father and I

00:12:30.000 --> 00:12:36.000
gradually kind of separated from each other.

00:12:36.000 --> 00:12:40.000
We still lived together, supported me,

00:12:40.000 --> 00:12:44.000
but he started spending more and more time with his girlfriend,

