00:15:26.000 --> 00:15:30.000
And then I get another phone call saying she died.

00:15:30.000 --> 00:15:32.000
And that was her life.

00:15:32.000 --> 00:15:35.000
That was the last 10 years of her life.

00:15:35.000 --> 00:15:37.000
And she says, beautiful, culture,

00:15:37.000 --> 00:15:43.000
educated, woman, never had a chance.

00:15:43.000 --> 00:15:46.000
With a medical install.

00:15:46.000 --> 00:15:49.000
Sure.

00:15:49.000 --> 00:16:00.000
And so you were in Los Angeles at that?

00:16:00.000 --> 00:16:02.000
I was in LA.

00:16:02.000 --> 00:16:06.000
Working and supporting myself and going to UCLA.

00:16:06.000 --> 00:16:12.000
And every spare moment I had was devoted to the Civil Rights Movement.

00:16:12.000 --> 00:16:15.000
So what were you, first of all, what were you studying at UCLA?

00:16:15.000 --> 00:16:17.000
Well, I didn't know what I wanted.

00:16:17.000 --> 00:16:20.000
I was lost.

00:16:20.000 --> 00:16:25.000
The whole UCLA scene was alien to me.

00:16:25.000 --> 00:16:29.000
I arrived on campus and there were all these middle class kids

00:16:29.000 --> 00:16:30.000
running around.

00:16:30.000 --> 00:16:34.000
I couldn't really identify what's anymore.

00:16:34.000 --> 00:16:39.000
But interestingly enough, I plunged into student politics,

00:16:39.000 --> 00:16:43.000
which is how I got involved in the Civil Rights Movement.

00:16:43.000 --> 00:16:48.000
And so I'm climbing the political ladder in UCLA.

00:16:48.000 --> 00:16:51.000
It came very active politically.

00:16:51.000 --> 00:16:55.000
Made some pretty heavy white contact.

00:16:55.000 --> 00:17:00.000
Howard Berman and Henry Waxman were part of their machine.

00:17:00.000 --> 00:17:05.000
And they came active in the National Student Association.

00:17:05.000 --> 00:17:14.000
Went to National Student Association conferences.

00:17:14.000 --> 00:17:22.000
And just started climbing the political ladder.

00:17:22.000 --> 00:17:23.000
Any way I could.

00:17:23.000 --> 00:17:25.000
What year about?

00:17:25.000 --> 00:17:30.000
Well, I actually interviewed UCLA in 58.

00:17:30.000 --> 00:17:34.000
So what was the National Student Association concerned with?

00:17:34.000 --> 00:17:37.000
What were the major issues, I guess, at that point?

00:17:37.000 --> 00:17:42.000
Well, the major issues were international.

00:17:42.000 --> 00:17:49.000
There was this cold war going on between International Union of Students,

00:17:49.000 --> 00:17:52.000
which I believe was a communist front.

00:17:52.000 --> 00:17:55.000
I know what's going on in the front.

00:17:55.000 --> 00:17:59.000
And I'll mention the International Student Conference.

00:17:59.000 --> 00:18:03.000
If I don't have them confused, I don't think I knew.

00:18:03.000 --> 00:18:09.000
And our people were being trained by the CIA

00:18:09.000 --> 00:18:13.000
and going off to conferences all over the world

00:18:13.000 --> 00:18:19.000
in this cold war to influence other student union.

00:18:19.000 --> 00:18:22.000
And there was some pretty hairy episode.

00:18:22.000 --> 00:18:32.000
You know, we had people, and we had half a dozen offices around the world.

00:18:32.000 --> 00:18:37.000
There was the International Student Conference,

00:18:37.000 --> 00:18:43.000
had a secretary in, in, in Europe.

00:18:43.000 --> 00:18:51.000
And the CIA was spending money and assigning,

00:18:51.000 --> 00:18:54.000
hemingwights to run this network.

00:18:54.000 --> 00:18:57.000
It was a CIA network.

00:18:57.000 --> 00:19:01.000
And the head of the network was a guy named Bob Kiley,

00:19:01.000 --> 00:19:03.000
who'd been president of National Student Association,

00:19:03.000 --> 00:19:06.000
which sent the whole network up.

00:19:06.000 --> 00:19:09.000
And...

00:19:11.000 --> 00:19:14.000
He became...

00:19:14.000 --> 00:19:17.000
why am I going to work for the CIA?

00:19:17.000 --> 00:19:22.000
And ultimately, he became Richard Helms Special Assistant.

00:19:22.000 --> 00:19:27.000
And there's some interesting stories about that.

00:19:27.000 --> 00:19:31.000
But back at UCLA, what were the primary things that you were involved in?

00:19:31.000 --> 00:19:34.000
Well, we got caught up on the whole thing.

00:19:34.000 --> 00:19:36.000
So we thought we were important,

00:19:36.000 --> 00:19:38.000
because we were a part of this.

00:19:38.000 --> 00:19:41.000
We didn't realize it was a CIA front.

00:19:41.000 --> 00:19:45.000
You know, we thought we were just students doing it.

00:19:45.000 --> 00:19:48.000
With certain foundations.

00:19:48.000 --> 00:19:51.000
And the youth and student foundations involved things.

00:19:51.000 --> 00:19:53.000
Can you imagine?

00:19:53.000 --> 00:19:57.000
You're running this network.

00:19:57.000 --> 00:20:00.000
And you have something called the Youth and Student Foundation,

00:20:00.000 --> 00:20:02.000
and it's absurd.

00:20:02.000 --> 00:20:04.000
You know, you might as well have said,

